{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17570074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17570074"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:37:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:37:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22661"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22661"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.33,0.18,0.23,0.22,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15608"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112179"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15608","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15608"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22661"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94244"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"12922"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45218"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45232"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112179"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-week history of vague, intermittent lower abdominal discomfort without radiation. She reports no weight loss, jaundice, change in bowel habit, fever, nausea, or vomiting. The symptoms are mild and not activity-limiting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has no significant medical history. She does not take any regular medications. She does not smoke and drinks two glasses of wine on weekends. There has been no recent travel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 126/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Abdominal examination is soft and non-tender with no palpable masses. There is no scleral icterus or peripheral stigmata of chronic liver disease. Her full blood count and liver function tests are all within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA CT scan is performed. The only abnormal finding is a well-circumscribed cystic lesion in the pancreatic tail measuring 18 mm, without solid components, mural nodules, or main pancreatic duct dilation (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance with discharge from follow-up","Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography","Computed tomography surveillance at one year","Endoscopic ultrasound-guided fine needle aspiration","Elective distal pancreatectomy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIncidental pancreatic cysts are frequently detected with modern imaging (see blue triangle in images below), particularly in middle-aged and older adults. The clinical task is to characterise the cyst, estimate malignancy risk, and choose between surveillance, further diagnostic work-up, or surgery. Magnetic resonance imaging with magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography provides superior contrast resolution for cyst morphology, septations, mural nodules, and communication with the pancreatic duct compared with computed tomography, and avoids ionising radiation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography\u003C/strong\u003E is the best next step because the computed tomography description suggests a small, asymptomatic cyst without worrisome features, yet computed tomography is limited in assessing ductal communication and subtle mural nodules. Magnetic resonance imaging refines risk stratification and guides whether surveillance alone is appropriate or whether endoscopic ultrasound is indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance with discharge from follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E is premature. Although many small cysts are benign, initial magnetic resonance imaging characterisation is recommended to confirm the absence of high-risk features and to determine an evidence-based surveillance plan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography surveillance at one year\u003C/strong\u003E is less appropriate as the immediate next step because it does not improve initial characterisation and exposes the person to repeat radiation. If surveillance is chosen after magnetic resonance imaging, interval and modality are tailored to cyst features, often favouring magnetic resonance imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopic ultrasound-guided fine needle aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E is typically reserved for cysts with worrisome or high-risk features on imaging, or where diagnosis remains uncertain after optimal non-invasive imaging. In a small cyst without concerning features, proceeding directly to invasive sampling is not indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElective distal pancreatectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for a small, asymptomatic cyst without mural nodules, solid components, or ductal dilation. Surgery is considered when high-risk features, cytology suggesting malignancy, or definite high-risk intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm are present, balancing operative morbidity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Incidental pancreatic cysts are common; magnetic resonance imaging with magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography refines characterisation and risk stratification.","High-risk or worrisome features on imaging guide the need for endoscopic ultrasound with fluid analysis or surgical referral; absent features favour imaging surveillance.","Cytology or resection is not first-line for small, asymptomatic cysts without concerning features on cross-sectional imaging."],"references":["Elta GH, Enestvedt BK, Sauer BG, et al. ACG Clinical Guideline: Diagnosis and Management of Pancreatic Cysts. Am J Gastroenterol 2018; 113:464\u2013479","Gardner TB, Park WG, Allen PJ. Diagnosis and Management of Pancreatic Cysts. Gastroenterology 2024; 167:454\u2013468","Vladut C, Bilous D, Ciocirlan. Real-Life Management of Pancreatic Cysts: Simplified Review of Current Guidelines. J Clin Med. 2023; 12:4020","Gaillard F, Silverstone L, Campos A, et al. Cystic lesions of the pancreas (differential). Reference article, Radiopaedia.org (Accessed on 26 Aug 2025) https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-1195"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94244"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22661"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22025"},{"type":"media","id":"22026"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22074"},{"type":"media","id":"22075"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22025"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/W2AtVyPgzYMKP6bxpHGZXtzf3C8V2B.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/W2AtVyPgzYMKP6bxpHGZXtzf3C8V2B.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":319}},{"type":"media","id":"22026","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22026"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/RkGOM4c96sEJqAO8GMN6JHvBX9AGCS.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/RkGOM4c96sEJqAO8GMN6JHvBX9AGCS.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":713,"height":828}}